<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Presumably from near Cul de Sac, Haiti, where Plumier collected numerous species. Lectotype (designated by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n20.2002.a12" author="Mottram, R" journalOrPublisher="Bradleya" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="79 - 120" refId="B19" refString="Mottram, R, 2002. Charles Plumier, the King's Botanist - his life and work. With a facsimile of the original cactus plates and text from Botanicon Americanum (1689-1697). Bradleya 20 (20): 79 - 120, DOI: https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n20.2002.a12" title="Charles Plumier, the King's Botanist - his life and work. With a facsimile of the original cactus plates and text from Botanicon Americanum (1689 - 1697)." url="https://doi.org/10.25223/brad.n20.2002.a12" volume="20" year="2002">Mottram 2002</bibRefCitation>
), plate t.21 in Plumier, which was cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lamarck, JB de" journalOrPublisher="Bioinformatics (Oxford, England)" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B13" refString="Lamarck, JB de, 1785. Dictionnaire encyclopedique de botanique 1: 536-544." title="Dictionnaire encyclopedique de botanique 1: 536 - 544." year="1785">Lamarck (1785)</bibRefCitation>
and thus formed part of the protologue. This includes an illustration of a fragment of a stem segment, flower and fruit.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Leptocereus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Leptocereus paniculatus" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paniculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Leptocereus paniculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is consistently recovered as closely related to the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. quadricostatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="quadricostatus">L. quadricostatus</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. grantianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="grantianus">L. grantianus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
clade (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogeny of Leptocereus with all major clades represented (sensu Barrios et al. 2020) and the new species L. velozianus included, resolved here as sister to L. demissus. Bootstrap values are given above the branches." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.172.59497.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/502596" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">1</figureCitation>
; see also 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00606-020-01693-5" author="Barrios, D" journalOrPublisher="Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B5" refString="Barrios, D, Arias, S, Gonzalez-Torres, LR, Majure, LC, 2020. Phylogeny and taxonomy of the genus Leptocereus (Cactaceae) inferred from chloroplast markers and morpho-anatomical evidence. Plant Systematics and Evolution 306: e63. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00606-020-01693-5" title="Phylogeny and taxonomy of the genus Leptocereus (Cactaceae) inferred from chloroplast markers and morpho-anatomical evidence. Plant Systematics and Evolution 306: e 63." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00606-020-01693-5" year="2020">Barrios et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), although the species is much more robust and treelike compared to the other two species. It is the only species on Hispaniola that has spineless, tuberculate fruits and forms large populations at lower elevations in seasonally dry tropical forest across the island (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Distribution map of L. demissus (black circles), L. paniculatus (open circles), and L. velozianus (black stars) on Hispaniola." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.172.59497.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/502599" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Photographic plate of L. paniculatus A habit B spiny trunk C apical, spiny, four-angled stems D fruiting stems and tuberculate fruit, and E longitudinal section of mature fruit. A, D from Majure 7817 B, C, E from Majure 6581. Photos by L. C. Majure." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.172.59497.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/502601" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
